hfl62LX14YqNpG0g0Tj6_Q
There are many reasons why I love this restaurant, so I'll share with you my "Top 5 Reasons You Should Dine At Fuego".  5. The place is f*cking charming as a mo-fo. If you want a romantic setting for date night, sit in the art gallery near the piano. If you want to dance after dark, sit outside on the hacienda style patio under the misters and shake your hips to the live band. If you want to get schwasted via craft cocktails, sit inside near the bar so your drinks won't have far to travel, thus arriving in your hand quicker from round to round.   4. It is locally-owned and operated by a staff that really knows how to make you feel welcome and appreciated. I've been here at least a half dozen times, over the course of the past 5 years, and see some of the same smiling staff members in the dining room and in the kitchen during that period of time. Everyone is gracious, everyone is pleasant, everyone is accommodating.  3. The crowd is a swath of humanity. Old folks, young folks, families with little kids, couples on date night, girlfriends meeting up to share a bottle of wine- there's a little bit of everyone dining and drinking at Fuego. You can't help but feel comfortable.   2. Latin-inspired food that looks and tastes like it's made from scratch. This is not a Mexican restaurant, even though some of the dishes are Mexican-inspired and feature common ingredients from that cuisine, so don't get it twisted. Empanadas, quesadillas, enchiladas, rellenos, TACOS (but tacos are only for lunch or happy hour). All excellent and anything including pernil will set you up for happiness. Get the cornbread as a side and perpare to make an "oh damn" face as you bite into it. You ever go to a restaurant and ignore the server schpiel about the specials? Don't ever do that here. Listen and take notes because you'll probably want to order one. Unless you are a vegan or a vegetarian because the specials always seem to star a meat of some sort. Also of note- the servers always tell you the price of the specials. I can't stand it when that important info is missing but it's always included at Fuego. My favorite steak besides the steaks coming off of my grill at home are served here. Don't pass up the ribeye!  1. Happy Hour. It's called Social Hour at Fuego and it offers discounts on drinks and appetizers that are hard to beat. You could show up with a few friends and do a tapas style dinner for not a lot of ca$h with $4 beers or $6 wine glasses. That would also afford you a chance to try a lot of the food to see what you might want to go steady with as an entree sometime.   It's not the cheapest restaurant (dinner entrees are all $25-$30 give or take a buck) but you'll enjoy every bite of your meal and you'll have impeccable service and probably have leftovers. With a few new drinking and dining establishments opening nearby, I imagine Fuego will only get busier.

