mp_Ws9ZJKcgSqKwr-2-Rgw
Dubina is 5 star, IMHO.  When they first opened, I was skeptical. A local brewery? In N. Glendale/Arrowhead? Not a chain? Crowdfunded?  A few months later and I can see they are growing the business and the operation in a smart way. I sure as hell hope they stay around for a very long time.   The interior of the space was all stark white walls and fluorescent lighting when they opened. I would have described it as "clean" but that'd be about it. The low, drop ceiling, chairs, tables, booths, barstools and concrete floors are still here but the lighting has been warmed up and there's a coat of paint on the walls now. It seems more welcoming and homier but you should focus on the beer when you visit.  I'm not a beer snob. Warm beer is about the only brew that I'll ever hate on. That being stated, I've gotten a beer education since I've begun to frequent Dubina. I know that a Gose is a sour, German style beer and that a sweet Barley Wine is the highest ABV beer and one of these will give you a nice beer buzz. I know that a nitro tap imparts those microscopic bubbles that give the Dubina Milk Stout its smooth and easy to drink features.   The staff always gives me a taste of the beers I'm unsure about and so far my faves are the Dubina Ale and the Milk Stout on nitro. Most of the brews are $5.   The food menu has also evolved from a brat and a pulled pork sammich to wings and amazing fresh-baked pretzel and a couple of salads. Everything on the menu is $10 or less.  It may not be the place to party, but it is a great spot to chill and have a conversation.  If you want to support a local business, and you like beer, and if you wanna play a life-sized Jenga game, all that and more is just north of Bell Rd. on 67th. Ave.

